Introduction¶

"Mandated by the Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act of 1993 and launched by the FBI on November 30, 1998, NICS is used by Federal Firearms Licensees (FFLs) to instantly determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Before ringing up the sale, cashiers call in a check to the FBI or to other designated agencies to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isn’t otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. More than 100 million such checks have been made in the last decade, leading to more than 700,000 denials" (FBI NICS).

For additional information on the data check here: https://github.com/BuzzFeedNews/nics-firearm-background-checks/blob/master/README.md .

I prefer to think of my questions which I want to answer after cleaning the dataset. However, the questions which I could think of would be linked to the changes of statistic in time. How the behaviour have changed during the time? Another interesting aspect might be the geographical distribution of the gun data (i.e, how it is different between the states).

For me it is helpfull to think of what I can take from the data when I do some EDA on the data. Therefore please check for my key questions in the Exploratory Data Analysis section.

discussion :

As can be seen the trend of total background check is positive with time. However, there exist several interesting patterns in this time-series:

  1. Since year 2009 onwards the checks show a significant rise! Is this due to the President Obamas election ?
  2. There exist 3 high outliers (red points in the upper figure)in tzhe time-series. I am really interested to know why they happend?

Conclusions¶

Results¶

The important findings in this dataset are listed as the following:

  • The overall background check has increased since mid-2006 for the whole country with a significant increasing trend.

  • Kentucky state shows a drastic jump in the number of total background checks since 2006 with the highest variations in time. However, Kentucky is not even among the top 20 gun buyers of 2019 according to https://www.statista.com/statistics/215655/number-of-registered-weapons-in-the-us-by-state/ .

  • There is a seasonal cycle in the data with a significant peak in December followed by March. This increase in the background check might correlate with the sales count for Christmas?!! Do the americans by guns as a gift? Look at this article from the Guardians : Guns top Christmas wish lists and the industry seems to be booming .

Limitations¶

  • The jump in Kentuky state might be explored with aditional information to find out the reason! Especially, the strange deviations since 2013 onwards.

  • It is not possible to link the background check data to sales rate or the amonunt of guns bought by americans. It only correlates good with December months were there are many guns purchased. It seems like each state has its own regulations.

  • The main problem by the data is, that it contains many nans for several feautres. From 52 initial columns, I only could use around 10 for analysis. The high number of nans makes it hard to impute them .

  • The none-coherent background check in time and location might be a great challenge to homogenoze the data for further studies and inject some unusual observation errors!
